label chapter7:

    # [Scene: Workshop | Morning]

    scene bg ch7_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low hum of a dehumidifier, the soft hiss of solder, distant gulls and the slap of tide against pilings.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, steady BGM—an anxious, measured rhythm]
    "You taste copper whenever you touch the metal model Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq is welding into shape. The workshop smells like salt, hot metal, and the lemon oil from Rosa's reclaimed tool box. Your fingers remember every"
    "fold of the maps you carried; they ache with the memory of work and worry."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "If we stack these units like this, they flex with the tide instead of pushing it back. The joints sit lower—less cost, less wall. People can stay."
    "You lean in, hand hovering over the miniature joint. The idea is both salvation and compromise: a way to temper Eloise Varela's hard line with something that won't uproot everyone. You feel hope, immediate and fragile, like glass tempered but not yet annealed."
    show mara_lin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "We need fail-safes—channels for sediment, places where marsh plants can reclaim after a high tide. If we only harden edges, we rebuild the same problem."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "We can put in breakaway segments where the marsh needs room. Modular, replaceable, community-maintainable. You draw the steward nodes; I’ll torque the anchors."
    "You both speak fast; plans tumble out in overlapping motion. The rhythm of making soothes you and tightens you at once—something practical to do with the gnawing anxiety under everything. Tools clink. The map on your knee bears smudges of both ink and rain."
    "Rosa arrives with a bundle of cordgrass and a thermos of thick coffee. She sets it down like an offering."
    show rosa_alvarez at right:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_alvarez "You two look like the tide did a duet on you. Speak clear. The people will want names and nights—don't give them excuses."

    mara_lin "We won't. We're proposing a hybrid. Something that grants safety goods promised by the Hall but keeps neighborhoods—keeps people—intact."

    rosa_alvarez "Good. Keep your eyes honest, child. Let them see the labor and risk with the plan."
    "A knock, light but determined: Kai slips in, mud on his boots, the Harbor Market's latest bulletin in hand."
    show kai_moreno at center:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_moreno "Samira said she could spare an hour. She wants to hear phrasing—what to tell council. Also,' (he drops his voice) 'there's murmurs. Eloise's team is already drafting talking points."
    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq's shoulders tighten at the name. You feel the room shift a degree colder."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "We need Samira to believe the hybrid is credible. She can stall if she trusts the data."

    mara_lin "Then we give her the data and the story."

    menu:
        "Lead with 'community safety' language":
            "You pick up the marker and write 'Community Safety' across the top of the presentation slide, imagining faces in the room reacting with relief."
        "Lead with 'stewardship and resilience' language":
            "You circle 'Stewardship & Resilience', thinking of Rosa's hands and the Flats' grasses; the words feel truer, but less instantly persuasive in a council chamber."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue"
    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq watches you select words like someone watching a rivet set. He shifts a small tool between his fingers."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "Whatever it is, don't let them flatten the labor. Don't let words erase the people who will do the work."
    "You look at the model, at the tiny channels where cordgrass will grow, and at the thin brass compass at your collar. The compass warms under your thumb, and for a moment it points not to north but to a stubborn need: keep people here, keep them whole."
    # [Scene: Rooftop Greenhouse | Late Afternoon]
    hide mara_lin
    hide rosa_alvarez
    hide kai_moreno

    scene bg ch7_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Bees in the trellises, the far rumble of road graders on a distant levee, intermittent wind through the greenhouse vents.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A slightly higher, hopeful thread overlays the undercurrent—still wary, still tight]
    "Samira arrives, clipboard held like a talisman. Her municipal vest sticks damp against her back; the city smells of wet pavement and printer ink where she came from the Hall."
    show samira_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    samira_chen "I can only ask for a delay if I present a credible alternative. They want a single headline: shield. They don't do nuance well in a one-hour vote."
    show mara_lin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "We give them a headline they can read without misplacing the footnotes."

    samira_chen "You know what I risk. My superiors—' (she stops, searching) '—they have deadlines and a board that loves numbers over people unless the people are already on a payroll."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "We give her numbers. Cost curves, maintenance estimates, a rollout schedule divided by neighborhood. We show how community labor cuts operating costs by—"

    samira_chen "And show how it reduces displacement metrics. I'll try."
    "You hand Samira a section of the model plan, your palms slightly muddy from the cordgrass. Her fingers tremble when she takes it; it's a small thing, but you register a human being squeezed between duty and conscience."
    show rosa_alvarez at center:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_alvarez "Remember—don't let them peddle fear for votes. Fear is a fast sale."

    mara_lin "We frame it so fear can't monopolize the narrative. We include contingency funds, training, local hiring schedules. We make it undeniable that this keeps people in their places."

    samira_chen "If I can stall for one more day—if I can get the advisory board meeting deferred—I can force a committee review. That buys you time to mobilize the proofs."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "Time is what we've been asking for."
    "You meet Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq's eyes over the prototype. There's a warmth there—an exhaustion shared—and something that feels like an unspoken promise to see this through. But you also feel the shear of politics: a schedule"
    "can be rigid; public sentiment can be fragile. The municipal machine has teeth and timers."

    menu:
        "Add a visual of people maintaining modules in the slides":
            "You sketch quick figures—neighbors swapping tools, Rosa kneeling in mud—imagining a councilor's gaze soften."
        "Keep visuals technical, emphasize costs and resilience stats":
            "You tidy the graphs into neat bars and lines, thinking this will speak to fiscal minds but not to wet hands."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue"

    samira_chen "Both will need to be there. Story and ledger. If you give me both, I can ask for a study session instead of an immediate vote."

    rosa_alvarez "Good. Make them sit with the humans behind the numbers."
    hide samira_chen
    show kai_moreno at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_moreno "And bring the market folks. If voices come from the people who live it, politicians start to feel called-out."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "I'll translate the tech into training modules. We can show how workshops will empower crews to repair and adapt."
    "You think of the volunteers who came last month—callused hands, kids learning to tie knots, neighbors swapping food for hours of labor. The image steadies the wobble in your stomach."
    # [Scene: Municipal Council | Evening]
    hide mara_lin
    hide rosa_alvarez
    hide kai_moreno

    scene bg ch7_453e40_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The murmur of councilors arranging papers, the soft chirp of a notification echoing from Eloise's AR glasses.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Tension returns, low strings matching the chamber's chill]
    show eloise_varela at left:
        zoom 0.7

    eloise_varela "We have a choice between decisive action and gradualism. The shield is decisive. It offers immediate reduction in risk."
    show mara_lin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "We don't have to call it gradualism. We call it sustainable."

    eloise_varela "And I welcome proposals from our citizens. The council will hear them. Time is the variable we cannot ignore."
    "Her words are smooth; you cannot tell whether the smile carries a blade. Samira looks at you briefly—complex, resigned, grateful; the look settles and shifts into the professional mask she must wear here."
    "You step forward to present. Your voice carries better than you expect—steady, slightly raw."

    mara_lin "Thank you. Our proposal centers on modular, community-maintainable defenses integrated with marsh restoration. It reduces capital cost and preserves neighborhoods, and it builds local capacity for long-term upkeep."

    "Councilor" "How do you account for storm surge events that require immediate, large-scale response?"

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "The modules are designed to be tied into temporary, deployable reinforcement. Think of them as a distributed system—some elements are flexible, others are sacrificial, designed to let marshes do the work post-storm."
    "You watch faces across the chamber shift. Some tilt toward curiosity; others tighten with the strain of political accounting. Eloise Varela's expression remains unreadable—a practiced neutrality. You remind yourself of Rosa's advice: don't expect a type of purity from the city. Expect work."
    show samira_chen at center:
        zoom 0.7

    samira_chen "We've run cost projections and displacement risk models. The hybrid shows a 40 Percentage reduction in the number of households flagged for relocation under the existing shield plan."
    "A murmur. Someone on the council scrawls a figure. Eloise Varela inclines her head, almost imperceptibly."

    eloise_varela "Those are promising numbers. Implementation logistics remain a concern, as well as investor assurances."
    "You can feel, like an undercurrent, how quickly the city's need for a headline can drown out the small print."

    "Councilor Two" "Who's responsible for maintenance? Who pays if modules fail?"

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "Local co-ops trained during rollout, municipal oversight funded by reallocated capital—community contracts for maintenance. We estimate initial investment is lower and community employment higher than the current shield model."
    "The back-and-forth stretches. You answer, then listen, then answer again. The exhaustion in your throat grows but the words keep coming—because words, here, can buy a day, a committee, a Plan B instead of bulldozers."
    # [Scene: Rooftop Greenhouse | After Council]
    hide eloise_varela
    hide mara_lin
    hide samira_chen

    scene bg ch7_453e40_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Wind threading through the trellises, a distant foghorn. The greenhouse vents rattle. Rain begins to spit, then fatten.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A steadying chord that edges toward urgency—hope threaded through apprehension]
    "You and Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq carry the prototype up the narrow service stair together, leaning into the wind that smells of metal and brine. The city below is a patchwork of lights and wet roofs. You"
    "feel both lighter—because the council listened longer than you dared hope—and heavier, because the listening hasn't yet become action."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "They asked good questions. Samira did what she could."
    show mara_lin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_lin "She did. But 'did' is not the same as 'will.'"

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "We did a thing people can hold on to. That counts. It counts a lot."
    "You stand close, shoulder to shoulder, watching the first real drops scatter on the glass dome. The wind lifts a stray braid of your hair. Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq reaches, tucking it behind your ear with a hand that smells faintly of solder and ocean. The gesture is ordinary, domestic, human."

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "Hey—you're doing the loud, ugly work. Let me help carry some of it."

    mara_lin "Your throat tightens in a familiar way—an old reflex against leaning too far into anything that could bind you. You want to reach for him and measure the promise with a measuring tape, to not be ruined by wanting."

    menu:
        "Take his hand":
            "You let your fingers close around his. The grip is solid and warm; the storm's arrival feels slightly less like a threat and more like something you might meet together."
        "Step back, keep the distance":
            "You close your fists instead and breathe out. The small warmth of his touch is gone, replaced by the cool, readying air—comfort kept carefully at arm's length."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue"
    "Thunder rumbles closer, not yet angry but insistent. The prototype hums faintly where its sensors watch the first gusts. You think of the Flats: the mud, the reed fences, Rosa stooped planting cordgrass into a future"
    "you hope will still be there. You think of Samira squeezed into this room, doing the best she could with teeth far sharper than her own."

    mara_lin "Tomorrow we start the field tests. If the modules hold, we get data; if they don't, we learn fast. Either way—"

    "Ibrahim 'Ibe' Rafiq" "—we're there with the people who will have to live with it."
    "There is a look in his eyes that is both pleading and steady. The clouds break a breath and the first heavier drops begin to streak the glass."
    "Your compass thumps warm at your collar. The rain hisses as it meets greenhouse glass. You stand on a rooftop between a council's long room and the Flats, between words that might buy time and a storm that will not wait for committees to finish."
    hide mara_lin

    scene bg ch7_453e40_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rain increasing, the soft creak of the prototype in the wind]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single elongated note that wants to resolve but doesn't]
    "You feel the city tilting toward a test that will prove plans in salt and wind instead of slides and projections. Your breath catches—the map in your pocket, Samira's constrained gratitude, Rosa's quiet counsel—everything coheres into one sharp, urgent edge."
    "The storm is coming. The field tests begin at dawn."

    scene bg ch7_453e40_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Tense BGM swells then holds]
    "You let the moment stretch, the pause like the taut line of a tide fence before the water hits."

    scene bg ch7_453e40_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fade Out]

    jump chapter8
